We must show that X_{\mathcal {R}} satisfies the closure condition described by the rule depicted above. For that, we assume that u_1,\ldots ,u_n lie in X_{\mathcal {R}} and we need to verify that v lies in X_{\mathcal {R}}. By definition, we therefore have 
 \scriptstyle \frac {\scriptstyle \vdots }{\scriptstyle u_i}
 derivations of each u_i and we need to find a derivation of v. We do this by combining the assumed derivations using the rule as follows to obtain a derivation of v:

html:li.html:p:
The rule 
 \scriptstyle \frac {\scriptstyle u_1\quad \ldots \quad  u_n}{\scriptstyle v}
 specifies a closure condition, and because S\in  \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}} we know that S is closed under it. Recalling the closure condition induced by a rule, we can immediately conclude v\in  S from u_1,\ldots ,u_n\in  S.

